<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Simple Waypoint Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        A generic marker, patrol node, path point, or trigger helper used by other Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Simple Waypoints Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Simple Waypoint</Bold> is a general-purpose Event Point. It does not spawn a person,
        vehicle, item, or visual effect by itself. Instead, it marks a position that other mission
        systems can use.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Simple Waypoints are commonly used as patrol route nodes, path positions, intermediate
        trigger points, switch/use detection points, and destinations or references for other Event
        Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Simple Waypoints do have one type-specific property: Delay. This is stored in
                    tenths of a second and controls how long an entity pauses at the waypoint before
                    continuing.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Uses
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>NPC patrol routes</Bold> - enemies or civilians can move through Simple Waypoints in group/order logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Vehicle patrol routes</Bold> - driver or vehicle logic can use waypoints as route positions.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Switch triggers</Bold> - a Simple Waypoint near a switch can detect player use, then activate another Event Point by dependency.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Path nodes</Bold> - movement or camera-style chains can use waypoint positions as intermediate locations.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Logic markers</Bold> - mission logic can reference a Simple Waypoint as a readable point in a dependency chain.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Delay
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Delay</Bold> is the Simple Waypoint's type-specific property. It is stored as a number
        of tenths of a second. The editor also shows the equivalent value in seconds.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>0</Bold> means no pause.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>10</Bold> means 1.0 second.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>25</Bold> means 2.5 seconds.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>100</Bold> means 10.0 seconds.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Use Delay when an entity should wait briefly before moving to its next waypoint. For patrols,
        this can make guards pause at corners, doorways, observation posts, or points of interest
        instead of moving continuously.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical use:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Keep most patrol waypoints at Delay 0, then add short delays only at places where
                    the character should visibly pause. This keeps routes responsive while still
                    making patrols feel intentional.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Creating a Simple Waypoint
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Simple</Bold> as the Event Point type.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the appropriate letter group and colour for the chain or logic it belongs to.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold>, then click the intended map position.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Delay</Bold> if an entity should pause at this waypoint.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Configure the trigger settings if the waypoint is being used as a trigger helper rather than only a movement node.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Group and Colour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Simple Waypoints often work best when their letter group and colour match the entity or
        mission logic that will use them. For example, a patroling NPC and its route waypoints should
        be easy to identify as part of the same chain.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        If several systems use Simple Waypoints in the same mission, use different colours or letter
        groups to keep patrol paths, trigger helper points, objective markers, and camera/path logic
        visually separate.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Trigger Helper Pattern
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Simple Waypoint can act as an invisible trigger helper. A common pattern is to place a
        Simple Waypoint near a switch, set it to detect the player using that switch area, then make
        another Event Point depend on the Simple Waypoint.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Player uses switch -&gt; Simple Waypoint activates -&gt; Dependent Event Point fires
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Troubleshooting
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">An entity does not pause at the waypoint</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm Delay is greater than 0.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Remember Delay is in tenths of a second, so 1 is only 0.1 seconds.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the entity is actually using this waypoint as part of its movement route.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">A dependency does not fire</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the dependent Event Point references the Simple Waypoint's Event Point number.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Simple Waypoint trigger condition can actually be satisfied.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the Simple Waypoint radius or trigger-specific values if it relies on player proximity or use.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">A patrol follows the wrong route</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check that the waypoint group and colour match the intended route logic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Keep unrelated Simple Waypoints in different groups or colours to avoid accidental route overlap.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Inspect Event Point numbers if the movement mode follows waypoints in numeric order.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
</FlowDocument>
